description: o Migrated 5th Signal Command’s portal, SharePoint 2007 to SharePoint 2010. Most requests were deliveried to customer within 72 hours from time of submission. o Completed 2 Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) requests that required 500 pages to be marked for redaction. Completed the FOIA requests within the regulatory period of 20 days. o Assisted Army’s Chief Information Office/G-6 with a pilot test for Metalogix Migration Manager. Recommended a DOIM C2 structure that was approved by the Army Chief of Staff and implemented by the U.S. Army.

description: Supervise the coordination and integration of the Department of Defense Future Vertical Lift/Joint Multi-Role (FVL/JMR) effort in accordance with the "Future Vertical Lift Strategic Plan for United States Department of Defense Vertical Lift Aircraft." Supports and executes the guidance and decisions of the Joint Council of Colonels and the FVL Executive Steering Group in the execution of the FVL Strategy. Leads the Joint Coordination and Integration Cell a Joint Staff office which coordinates, integrates and synchronizes the Services, Joint Staff and OSD efforts to develop the next generation FVL/JMR aircraft. Develops, in coordination with the ESG and CoC, plans, policies and procedures to support and assist the Services in their Science and Technology, Acquisition and Testing programs for the FVL/JMR effort. Facilitate, assist and provide liaison to the Joint Staff the Office of the Secretary of Defense and the Services on the JCIDS process. Provide interface and guidance to established and future FVL/JMR working groups. In conjunction with OSD and the CoC, facilitates FVL/JMR efforts with Congress, Industry and Academia. Prepares written reports and briefings to senior leadership on FVL/JMR matters.

description: Commander of 1st Battalion, 214th Aviation Regiment, the largest GSAB in the Army, forward deployed in Germany simultaneously supporting three COCOMs (EUCOM, AFRICOM and CENTCOM). Responsible for the readiness and welfare of over 650 Soldiers, DA civilians, local nationals and their Families. description: Deputy Brigade Commander for the forward deployed 82nd Airborne Division's Combat Aviation Brigade consisting of an Air Cavalry Squadron, an Attack/Reconnaissance Battalion, an Assault Helicopter Battalion, two General Support Aviation Battalions and an Aviation Support Battalion. Oversees the employment of Task Force Pegasus's 150 rotary wing aircraft and 3200 personnel while deployed to Operation Enduring Freedom X. Primarily responsible for the prioritization, synchronization and resourcing of the CAB's Operations, Intelligence, Communications and the integration of 30 OH-58D Kiowa Warriors, 46 UH-60L Blackhawks, 27 AH-64 Apache Longbows, 24 HH-60 MEDEVAC, 23 CH-47D/F Chinooks as well as our coalition (Australian) partner aircraft. Responsible for all aspects of rotary wing support in the Joint and NATO environment of ISAF's Regional Command South and West.

description: Brigade Operations Officer for the 82nd Airborne Division's Combat Aviation Brigade consisting of an Air Cavalry Squadron, an Attack/Reconnaissance Battalion, an Assault Helicopter Battalion, a General Support Aviation Battalion and an Aviation Support Battalion. Oversees the employment of the 82nd CAB's 117 rotary wing aircraft and 2800 troopers during garrison, combat and contingency operations. Primarily responsible for the prioritization, synchronization and resourcing of the CAB's METL focused training and combat readiness and the integration of 30 OH-58D Kiowa Warriors, 38 UH-60L Blackhawks, 24 AH-64D Apaches, 12 UH-60A MEDEVAC, 13 CH-47F Chinooks and over 500 pieces of ground support vehicles.

description: Brigade Aviation Officer of 2nd Brigade Combat Team (Airborne) (BCT) deployed to Iraq for Operation Iraqi Freedom as the first surge brigade. Serves as the aviation subject matter expert for the BCT Commander, advising him on employment of attack, reconnaissance, assault and general support aviation, as well as organic unmanned aerial systems. Responsible for advising the BCT commander and staff on the status and availability of aviation assets and their capabilities and limitations. Recommend and coordinate priorities and allocations of aviation assets across the battle space. Additionally, integrate Army Airspace Command and Control (A2C2) requirements for the BCT, communicate any airspace changes to the airspace users and manage the airspace above the BCT. Assigned additional responsibility as the BCT Effects Coordinator for all lethal and non-lethal fires and effects.

description: Executive Officer for 4th Squadron, 2nd Armored Cavalry Regiment (OIF) conducting combat operations while attached to 1st Armored Division. Managed 99 Officers and 348 soldiers, 24 OH-58D Kiowa Warrior Helicopters and 8 UH-60L Blackhawk Helicopters and 86 Tactical Vehicles. Prepared to assume command at any time. Responsible for directing, supervising and coordinating Primary and Special Staff efforts. During combat operations runs the Squadron Tactical Operations Center to effectively track current operations maintain routine reporting requirements, manage liaison personnel, plan future operations and ensure all combat support and combat service support is planned in consonance with the commander's intent. Executive maintenance manager for the Squadron's aircraft, vehicle and ground support equipment, ensuring the Squadron remains mission capable and prepared.

description: Tactical Operations Center (TOC/Attack/Cavalry Observe/Controller (O/C) at the Joint Readiness Training Center (JRTC). Responsible to coach, teach, mentor aviation task force commanders and staffs to execute their wartime mission in a demanding, realistic, joint and combined arms training environment. Provide objective feedback based on doctrine conducive to learning and professional growth through the formal and informal After Action Reviews (AAR) to ten aviation task forces rotations per year, integrating special operations forces, Air Force and Naval assets in a seamless joint and combined arms training environment. Responsible for maintaining and training 31 Aviation Observer/Controllers, ensuring the Aviation Division develops doctrinal sound Aviation O/Cs.

description: A Troop/2nd Squadron, 17th Cavalry Regiment, Commander of an OH-58D Kiowa Warrior equipped Air Cavalry Troop in the 101st Airborne Division (Air Assault). Primarily mission is the effective tactical employment of an Air Cavalry Troop to conduct reconnaissance and security operations in support of Division level combined arms operations. Responsible for the leadership, training, morale, welfare, discipline and safety of 27 soldiers. Responsible for the maintenance and accountability of eight OH-58D Kiowa Warriors, three tactical vehicles and all accompanying equipment valued at over $40 Million. Additionally responsible to hone the soldier's warfighting skills and ensure the Troop's readiness to deploy within 36 hours by air, rail or sea. Responsible for the professional development of all assigned personnel and primary trainer of 19 assigned combat aviators.

description: Squadron Personnel and Administration Officer in the 2nd Squadron, 17th Cavalry Regiment, 101st Airborne Division (Air Assault). Responsible for the 88 Officers and 245 Enlisted Soldiers. Principal advisor to the Squadron Commander on Personnel and Administration actions. Directs personnel activities and services to include correspondence, evaluation reports, awards, finance, files, records management and strength accounting procedures while enforcing the commander's intent. As the Administration and Logistical Operations Center (ALOC) commander, directs all support operations, Unit Ministry Team, Medical Aid Station, Casualty Evacuation, and unit personnel replacement operations in all environments. Additional duties include Postal Officer and Protocol Officer.

description: Aircraft Maintenance Operations Platoon Leader for an Aviation Intermediate Maintenance (AVIM) company in the 101st Airborne Division (Air Assault). Responsible for the training, supervision and welfare of 3 Warrant Officers and 170 Enlisted Soldiers in twelve different Military Operational Specialties (MOS). Plans, coordinates and directs all helicopter subsystem repairs for over 83 helicopters throughout the Aviation Brigade. Ensures quality, responsive and safe completion of work orders assigned to various platoon sections to include: airframe, powertrain, powerplant, pneudraulics, machine, welding, armament, electrical, battery and avionics shops. Responsible for the readiness, accountability and proper employment of over $10 Million worth of vehicles, tools and support equipment. Perform duties as an OH-58D Kiowa Warrior Aeroscout Pilot.

description: Battalion Logistics Officer (S4) for an AH-64 Apache Attack Helicopter Battalion forward deployed in Germany. Primary staff officer responsible for the logistical support of 34 helicopters, 68 vehicles and 296 personnel. Property Book Officer for over $450 Million of mission and installation property.
